<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many calories does a cat need per day?", answer: "An average 10-pound adult indoor cat needs approximately 200-250 calories per day. The exact amount depends on age, activity level, and whether the cat lives indoors or outdoors. Kittens need significantly more calories per pound of body weight (about 2.5 times their resting energy requirement) to support growth, while senior cats typically need fewer calories due to reduced activity." },
  { question: "How do I calculate my cat's calorie needs?", answer: "Use the Resting Energy Requirement (RER) formula: RER = 70 x (body weight in kg ^ 0.75). Then multiply by a life-stage factor: 2.5 for kittens, 1.2 for normal adult cats, and 1.0 for senior or inactive cats. Adjust further for activity level (multiply by 0.8 for inactive, 1.0 for moderate, 1.2 for active) and add 5-10% for outdoor cats who need extra energy for thermoregulation." },
  { question: "Should I feed my cat wet food or dry food?", answer: "Both wet and dry food can provide complete nutrition, but many veterinarians recommend incorporating wet food because cats naturally have a low thirst drive and get much of their moisture from food. Wet food typically contains 70-80% water compared to 10% in dry food. A combination of both often works well. When using this calculator, check the calorie content on your specific food's label, as it varies widely between brands." },
  { question: "How often should I feed my cat?", answer: "Most veterinarians recommend feeding adult cats 2-3 meals per day on a consistent schedule. Free-feeding (leaving dry food out all day) can lead to overeating and obesity, especially for indoor cats. Kittens under 6 months should eat 3-4 times daily. Measured meal feeding gives you better control over portions and makes it easier to notice appetite changes that could indicate health problems." },
  { question: "Do indoor cats need fewer calories than outdoor cats?", answer: "Yes, indoor cats typically need 5-10% fewer calories than outdoor cats of the same size and age. Outdoor cats burn extra energy through increased physical activity, thermoregulation in varying weather conditions, and generally having larger territories to patrol. Indoor cats are more prone to obesity because they are less active, so portion control is especially important." }
]) %>

<%= calculator_schema_with_ratings(
  name: "Cat Food Calculator",
  description: "Calculate your cat's daily calorie needs and food portions based on weight, age, activity level, and indoor/outdoor lifestyle.",
  url: pets_cat_food_url,
  category: "HealthApplication",
  calculator_slug: "cat-food"
) %>

